1
00:02:00,353 --> 00:02:04,016
- Hi, Cary.
- Hello, Sara.

2
00:02:04,124 --> 00:02:06,024
As usual, Cary,
you're way ahead of me.

3
00:02:06,126 --> 00:02:09,527
I haven't even had time to think
of my trees, much less get them pruned.

4
00:02:09,629 --> 00:02:11,927
Oh! I can't take
credit for that.

5
00:02:12,031 --> 00:02:14,625
Martin always made the arrangements
with the nursery.

6
00:02:14,734 --> 00:02:19,467
After his death, the service
just automatically continued.

7
00:02:19,572 --> 00:02:23,064
Not that i haven't the time. With
the children away except for weekends,

8
00:02:23,176 --> 00:02:25,576
- I've got nothing but time.
- Yes, i know.

9
00:02:25,678 --> 00:02:28,238
That's enough about that.
Let's have our lunch. It's all ready.

10
00:02:28,348 --> 00:02:31,943
- Darling, I can't have lunch.
- Oh?

11
00:02:32,051 --> 00:02:35,282
I would have phoned, but i wanted
to bring back the dishes i borrowed.

12
00:02:35,388 --> 00:02:38,585
Sometimes i think you're smart
not to be a club woman.

13
00:02:38,691 --> 00:02:41,387
Sometimes i wonder,
but it's just not for me.

14
00:02:41,494 --> 00:02:44,395
- I hope you didn't go to trouble.
- I didn't.

15
00:02:44,497 --> 00:02:48,058
It's George. He just phoned.
He's bringing out a weekend guest.

16
00:02:48,168 --> 00:02:50,432
Last-minute notice, as usual.

17
00:02:50,537 --> 00:02:53,802
What with a hundred other things to do,
i've got to dig up a date tonight...

18
00:02:53,907 --> 00:02:57,138
- For this Mr. Allenby.
- A date?

19
00:02:57,243 --> 00:03:01,680
Look, he's 40, which means he'll
consider any female over 18 too old.

20
00:03:01,781 --> 00:03:04,682
We might as well face it.
I've got to be off.

21
00:03:04,784 --> 00:03:09,346
Oh, how about joining us tonight
at the club for dinner?

22
00:03:09,455 --> 00:03:12,356
Well, no, Sara,
I don't think I'd better.

23
00:03:12,458 --> 00:03:16,292
Don't be silly. I'll phone Harvey.
Pick you up around 7:30.

24
00:03:16,396 --> 00:03:20,059
- Harvey?
- Oh, well, at least he's available.

25
00:03:20,166 --> 00:03:22,396
- Bye, darling.
- Good-bye.

26
00:03:25,905 --> 00:03:30,239
- Could i help you, Mrs. Scott?
- Well, yes, thank you.

27
00:03:36,249 --> 00:03:39,013
- Just put it right there.
- All right.

28
00:03:39,118 --> 00:03:42,451
- Would you like some hot coffee?
- Yeah, thanks.

29
00:03:44,257 --> 00:03:46,657
Perhaps you'd like
to share my lunch with me.

30
00:03:46,759 --> 00:03:50,695
My friend couldn't stay. I have plenty
of food. Chicken, salad and rolls.

31
00:03:50,797 --> 00:03:55,063
- Just a roll and some coffee will do.
- All right.

32
00:03:55,168 --> 00:03:57,898
- Won't you sit down?
- Mm-hmm.

33
00:04:08,448 --> 00:04:12,680
I was just wondering
if there's much to be done.

34
00:04:12,785 --> 00:04:16,846
- Everything looks so wonderful.
- Not much.

35
00:04:27,667 --> 00:04:33,037
Do you think you'll finish today
or will you have to come back?

36
00:04:33,139 --> 00:04:35,733
Well, probably will.

37
00:04:38,578 --> 00:04:42,241
I often wish I knew more
about gardening.

38
00:04:42,348 --> 00:04:44,646
Do you think
I ought to take it up?

39
00:04:44,751 --> 00:04:48,710
Only if you think
you'd like it.

40
00:04:49,822 --> 00:04:54,384
- I'm Mrs. Scott.
- Yes, I know.

41
00:04:54,494 --> 00:04:58,863
- I'm Ron Kirby.
- Oh, you're Mr. Kirby's son.

42
00:04:58,965 --> 00:05:03,664
Mm-hmm. I took over the nursery
three years ago when my father died.

43
00:05:03,770 --> 00:05:06,967
Have you been coming here
ever since?

44
00:05:07,073 --> 00:05:10,338
Mm-hmm. Every spring and every autumn.

45
00:05:10,443 --> 00:05:13,674
This may be my last year.

46
00:05:13,780 --> 00:05:18,808
At agricultural school, I got interested
in trees. So I started growing them.

47
00:05:20,553 --> 00:05:24,284
- What kind of trees?
- All kinds.

48
00:05:24,390 --> 00:05:29,020
White fir, Douglas fir,
silver tip spruce.

49
00:05:29,128 --> 00:05:32,256
- Do I have any?
- [Chuckles] No.

50
00:05:33,833 --> 00:05:36,802
But you have some
just as interesting.

51
00:05:36,903 --> 00:05:40,168
Like this Koelreuteria.

52
00:05:40,273 --> 00:05:44,733
In china where it comes from,
they call it the Golden Rain tree.

53
00:05:46,179 --> 00:05:48,374
Beautiful, isn't it?

54
00:05:48,481 --> 00:05:52,144
They say it can only thrive
near a home where there's love.

55
00:05:52,251 --> 00:05:54,947
- It's a beautiful legend.
- Mm-hmm.

56
00:05:55,054 --> 00:05:59,286
Well, I'd better
get back to work.

57
00:05:59,392 --> 00:06:02,190
Thank you for the coffee.

58
00:06:13,973 --> 00:06:16,965
- [Girl] Mother?
- [Boy] Hey, Mother!

59
00:06:17,076 --> 00:06:19,636
Here I am!

60
00:06:21,247 --> 00:06:24,045
Hello, darling!
- Hi!

61
00:06:24,150 --> 00:06:26,050
- Ned
- Hi, mom.

62
00:06:26,152 --> 00:06:28,211
I didn't expect you home
until tomorrow.

63
00:06:28,321 --> 00:06:30,346
I didn't have a class today
so I phoned Kay from Princeton...

64
00:06:30,456 --> 00:06:34,415
I was catching up on some case
histories... bane of the social worker...

65
00:06:34,527 --> 00:06:36,927
- So I brought them along.
- When's dinner?

66
00:06:37,029 --> 00:06:39,054
I've been invited out
for dinner.

67
00:06:39,165 --> 00:06:41,463
- Where are you going?
- Sarah's giving a party at the club.

68
00:06:41,567 --> 00:06:43,933
I'll have to get dressed. Harvey's
going to pick me up in a little while.

69
00:06:44,036 --> 00:06:47,335
Harvey?

70
00:06:47,440 --> 00:06:50,898
Oh, that's all right.
I'll go fix the cocktails.

71
00:06:51,010 --> 00:06:55,413
- Harvey likes my martinis.
- Ned, the martini wizard.

72
00:06:55,515 --> 00:06:59,645
- Have you been seeing much of Harvey?
- No, dear, he's been out of town.

73
00:06:59,752 --> 00:07:01,947
- Florida, I think.
- I like Harvey.

74
00:07:02,054 --> 00:07:05,148
He's pleasant, amusing,
and he acts his age.

75
00:07:05,258 --> 00:07:08,352
If there's anything I can't stand,
it's an old goat.

76
00:07:08,461 --> 00:07:13,956
As Freud says, when we reach
a certain age, sex becomes incongruous.

77
00:07:14,066 --> 00:07:16,728
I think Harvey understands that.

78
00:07:16,836 --> 00:07:20,272
- All in all, he's remarkably civilized.
- ????[Orchestra]

79
00:07:20,373 --> 00:07:23,035
And the only bachelor
around here.

80
00:07:23,142 --> 00:07:25,406
I'll admit,
he does have his drawbacks.

81
00:07:25,511 --> 00:07:27,672
He talks too much
about his health,

82
00:07:27,780 --> 00:07:30,442
but when you get to be his age,
it's understandable.

83
00:07:30,550 --> 00:07:32,745
Of course, it's normal to
fall apart as one grows older.

84
00:07:32,852 --> 00:07:35,286
But I can see
it might be hard to accept.

85
00:07:35,388 --> 00:07:39,552
Although naturally it doesn't matter
as much with men as it does with women.

86
00:07:39,659 --> 00:07:42,924
But, I guess Harvey's
intelligent enough anyway to...

87
00:07:43,029 --> 00:07:44,997
Are you reading this?

88
00:07:46,432 --> 00:07:49,492
- What, dear?
- [Wolf Whistle]

89
00:07:49,602 --> 00:07:53,163
It's about time you wore something
besides that old black velvet.

90
00:07:53,272 --> 00:07:55,900
- Is it?
- Of course.

91
00:07:56,008 --> 00:07:59,535
Personally, I never subscribed
to that old Egyptian custom.

92
00:07:59,645 --> 00:08:01,806
- At least I think it was Egypt.
- What egyptian custom?

93
00:08:01,914 --> 00:08:05,816
Of walling up the widow alive in the
funeral chamber of her dead husband...

94
00:08:05,918 --> 00:08:07,886
along with
his other possessions.

95
00:08:07,987 --> 00:08:10,683
The theory being that
she was a possession too.

96
00:08:10,790 --> 00:08:15,750
She was supposed to journey into death
with him. The community saw to it.

97
00:08:15,862 --> 00:08:19,491
- Of course, that doesn't happen anymore.
- Doesn't it?

98
00:08:19,599 --> 00:08:21,999
Well, perhaps not in Egypt.

99
00:08:22,101 --> 00:08:24,501
- What do you mean?
- Oh, nothing. Let's go downstairs.

100
00:08:31,477 --> 00:08:33,377
Holy cats, Mother.

101
00:08:34,814 --> 00:08:38,181
I've had it for quite a while.
I just haven't worn it.

102
00:08:38,284 --> 00:08:41,481
- Do you like it?
- I guess it's all right.

103
00:08:41,587 --> 00:08:43,919
- But isn't it cut kind of low?
- [Doorbell Ringing]

104
00:08:44,023 --> 00:08:45,923
Hope it doesn't
scare Harvey off.

105
00:08:46,025 --> 00:08:49,825
- A typical Oedipus reaction.
- A what?

106
00:08:49,929 --> 00:08:53,194
A son subconsciously resents his
mother being attractive to other men.

107
00:08:53,299 --> 00:08:55,392
We call it an Oedipus complex.

108
00:08:55,501 --> 00:08:59,130
- Happens all the time.

109
00:08:59,238 --> 00:09:02,571
- Good evening, Harvey.
- Cary, my dear! Well!

110
00:09:02,675 --> 00:09:04,540
- And Kay!
- Hi, Harvey.

111
00:09:04,644 --> 00:09:07,169
- You'll have a cocktail before you go?
- We have time.

112
00:09:07,280 --> 00:09:12,274
- He's mixed it especially for you.
- Thank you.

113
00:09:12,385 --> 00:09:14,444
- We've missed you.
- I'm glad.

114
00:09:14,554 --> 00:09:17,990
- Did you enjoy Florida?
- Perfect, Kay, perfect. Cary!

115
00:09:18,090 --> 00:09:20,684
I discovered one of the most
wonderful doctors down there.

116
00:09:20,793 --> 00:09:23,694
Cured one of my eternal colds,
like that!

117
00:09:23,796 --> 00:09:27,391
- Mom, Harvey, the Scott special.
- Thank you, Ned.

118
00:09:27,500 --> 00:09:32,028
- Thank you.
- Mmm!

119
00:09:32,138 --> 00:09:34,129
Excellent, my boy! Excellent!

120
00:09:34,240 --> 00:09:36,936
I'm not sure the gin is as good
as the brand i usually use,

121
00:09:37,043 --> 00:09:38,943
but the vermouth is fair.

122
00:09:39,045 --> 00:09:41,206
[Kay] You mean
those two little drops you put in?

123
00:09:41,314 --> 00:09:44,943
Kay, I hope for the sake
of my liver you've miscounted.

124
00:09:47,053 --> 00:09:49,521
Cary, you're looking
lovely tonight.

125
00:09:49,622 --> 00:09:53,080
- That color becomes you.
Well, thank you, Harvey.

126
00:09:53,192 --> 00:09:56,628
Ned was afraid the dress
might frighten you.

127
00:09:56,729 --> 00:10:00,825
It would take more...
perhaps I should say, less to scare me.

128
00:10:00,933 --> 00:10:04,562
No, thank you, Ned.
One cocktail is my limit.

129
00:10:04,670 --> 00:10:08,003
You know,
my reform started...

130
00:10:08,107 --> 00:10:11,508
the night your father
won this trophy.

131
00:10:11,611 --> 00:10:15,069
He filled it with champagne
and made us drink it.

132
00:10:15,181 --> 00:10:17,308
[Sighing]
I can still remember it.

133
00:10:17,416 --> 00:10:21,853
- How many of you were there?
- Not enough.

134
00:10:21,954 --> 00:10:25,890
- I think we better start, don't you?
- Yes, Harvey.

135
00:10:35,167 --> 00:10:37,499
- Cary! Hi, Harvey.
- Hello, Bill.

136
00:10:37,603 --> 00:10:40,731
- We never see you anymore.
- Cary, dear, it's been ages.

137
00:10:40,840 --> 00:10:44,571
Ann and I were laughing
the other night about the time Martin...

138
00:10:44,677 --> 00:10:48,773
Here you are. You can have her later.
Come on, darling.

139
00:10:48,881 --> 00:10:52,874
[Man] Cary!
My favorite woman. What'll it be?

140
00:10:52,985 --> 00:10:55,510
- We had a martini at the house...
- Never switch the pitch.

141
00:10:55,621 --> 00:10:57,919
- Same for you?
- Nothing for me. I've had my quota.

142
00:10:58,024 --> 00:11:01,084
You'll need more than one to see you
through this party, all my fault too.

143
00:11:01,193 --> 00:11:03,423
- And i've got him for the whole weekend.
- George! Hush.

144
00:11:03,529 --> 00:11:06,930
Tom, Cary. I want you to meet
Miss Frisbee, Mr. Allenby, Mrs. Scott.

145
00:11:07,033 --> 00:11:08,933
- Mrs. Scott.
- How do you do?

146
00:11:09,035 --> 00:11:11,936
Hello. I've been telling
your Mr. Allenby...

147
00:11:12,038 --> 00:11:14,700
He's awfully hard to resist.

148
00:11:14,807 --> 00:11:16,707
Seems to be mutual.

149
00:11:16,809 --> 00:11:18,800
- Sara!
- Hello, Sara, Cary.

150
00:11:18,911 --> 00:11:20,879
Did you see? The Nortons
are here together. After all the talk...

151
00:11:20,980 --> 00:11:23,847
- What talk?
- You know what everyone said.

152
00:11:23,949 --> 00:11:26,247
- No, but i'm sure you do.
- [Clearing Throat]

153
00:11:26,352 --> 00:11:30,584
Cary, oh, darling! How wonderful
to see you. I hardly recognized her.

154
00:11:30,690 --> 00:11:33,557
It's indecent to have two grown
children and look as young as you do.

155
00:11:33,659 --> 00:11:37,288
There's nothing like red for
attracting attention, is there?

156
00:11:37,396 --> 00:11:41,059
I suppose that's why so few widows wear
it. They'd have to be so careful.

157
00:11:41,167 --> 00:11:43,067
- Hello, Howard.
- Hi!

158
00:11:43,169 --> 00:11:46,195
- How about a dance?
- [Sara] Go ahead, Cary.

159
00:11:46,305 --> 00:11:49,103
All right. I'd like to.

160
00:11:49,208 --> 00:11:51,836
That was a horrid thing to say, Mona.

161
00:11:51,944 --> 00:11:53,844
What do you mean?

162
00:11:53,946 --> 00:11:56,574
I was only trying to cheer her up
by telling her how lovely she looked.

163
00:11:56,682 --> 00:12:00,174
- But she didn't seem to need it.
- Shall we have a drink?

164
00:12:00,286 --> 00:12:03,016
- How are mary and the children?
- Everybody's down with the flu.

165
00:12:03,122 --> 00:12:06,717
- I'm sorry.
- House is like a hospital.

166
00:12:06,826 --> 00:12:09,693
Now i'm glad i did.
[Chuckles]

167
00:12:12,298 --> 00:12:16,234
You're beautiful, Cary.
Too beautiful to be lonely.

168
00:12:19,205 --> 00:12:23,107
I can never decide whether Howard's
wife is a saint or just not very bright.

169
00:12:23,209 --> 00:12:25,473
She stays at home alone
night after night.

170
00:12:25,578 --> 00:12:28,775
- Yes, but she has the children.
- Even if she hasn't got Howard?

171
00:12:28,881 --> 00:12:34,012
- What does that mean?
- Don't bristle. Did i mention cary?

172
00:12:34,120 --> 00:12:37,749
I'm beginning to think
you have an evil mind.

173
00:12:37,857 --> 00:12:39,825
Now, really.

174
00:12:44,063 --> 00:12:48,363
- It's much nicer out here, isn't it?
- Yes.

175
00:12:48,467 --> 00:12:51,368
That's where they're going
to build a new swimming pool.

176
00:12:51,470 --> 00:12:53,370
- Oh?

177
00:12:55,274 --> 00:12:58,072
That's a wonderful place for it.

178
00:12:58,177 --> 00:13:00,702
When do you think they'll...

179
00:13:02,681 --> 00:13:06,640
Why don't we meet in new york?
I know a place.

180
00:13:06,752 --> 00:13:09,778
Howard, let's forget
you said that.

181
00:13:12,591 --> 00:13:16,254
I'm sorry, Cary.
I don't know what got into me.

182
00:13:16,362 --> 00:13:20,628
I know you're not like that.
I apologize for what I said.

183
00:13:20,733 --> 00:13:23,566
That's all right, Howard.

184
00:13:23,669 --> 00:13:27,070
- But I don't apologize for wanting you.
- [Sighs]

185
00:13:33,245 --> 00:13:36,339
Why didn't Ned tell me
about you before?

186
00:13:36,448 --> 00:13:39,212
Think of all the time
we've wasted.

187
00:13:39,318 --> 00:13:42,845
You're off on a tangent.
Your values are confused.

188
00:13:42,955 --> 00:13:44,855
I don't get it.

189
00:13:44,957 --> 00:13:50,554
The basic values of the sex attraction
between man and woman are...

190
00:13:50,663 --> 00:13:53,393
Oh, Mother and Harvey.

191
00:13:53,499 --> 00:13:56,332
Well, i'll try to explain,
but not here.

192
00:14:02,441 --> 00:14:04,568
Here you are.

193
00:14:04,677 --> 00:14:07,043
- Would you like a nightcap?
- No, thank you, Cary.

194
00:14:07,146 --> 00:14:10,445
It's way past my bedtime.
It's been a wild night for me.

195
00:14:10,549 --> 00:14:13,541
I've enjoyed every minute of it.
I always enjoy being with you.

196
00:14:13,652 --> 00:14:15,586
Thank you.
I feel the same.

197
00:14:15,688 --> 00:14:17,588
- Have your key?
- Yes.

198
00:14:21,260 --> 00:14:24,286
Now do you understand that much?

199
00:14:25,397 --> 00:14:27,729
Frankly, no. But...

200
00:14:27,833 --> 00:14:30,529
All right, I'll...
I'll try again.

201
00:14:36,508 --> 00:14:39,238
Cary...

202
00:14:39,345 --> 00:14:43,679
I don't know whether you're ready
to think about marrying again.

203
00:14:43,782 --> 00:14:47,548
Well, no, l...
I don't think I'm ready.

204
00:14:47,653 --> 00:14:51,248
Of course I realize I'm not
very romantic or impetuous...

205
00:14:51,357 --> 00:14:55,088
But then, you'd hardly
want that sort of thing.

206
00:14:55,194 --> 00:14:58,027
I'm sure you feel as I do.

207
00:14:58,130 --> 00:15:03,033
That companionship and affection
are the important things.

208
00:15:04,637 --> 00:15:07,538
I could give you those, Cary.

209
00:15:12,044 --> 00:15:16,947
Well, I won't press you
for a decision now.

210
00:15:20,352 --> 00:15:23,515
- Good night, dear.
- Good night, Harvey.

211
00:15:29,828 --> 00:15:34,128
You really didn't want to be
a football captain. You wanted love.

212
00:15:34,233 --> 00:15:37,031
- Yes.
- No, not the romantic nonsense.

213
00:15:37,136 --> 00:15:40,537
I mean, basic love,
the desire to be liked.

214
00:15:40,639 --> 00:15:43,870
Football was merely
a means to the end.

215
00:15:43,976 --> 00:15:46,410
Of course,
you do have the build for it.

216
00:15:46,512 --> 00:15:49,174
How can anyone so little
be so smart?

217
00:15:49,281 --> 00:15:51,306
And yet so pretty?

218
00:16:36,362 --> 00:16:39,525
- I'll see you Tuesday.
- Well, how long does this go on?

219
00:16:39,631 --> 00:16:41,531
Oh, you mean the pruning.

220
00:16:41,633 --> 00:16:44,101
He was supposed to come back
a couple of weeks ago and finish up.

221
00:16:44,203 --> 00:16:47,263
- I almost gave him up for lost.
- The independent type, huh?

222
00:16:47,373 --> 00:16:49,603
- Good-bye, darling.
- Good-bye, Sara.

223
00:16:50,943 --> 00:16:52,843
Hello there.

224
00:16:52,945 --> 00:16:56,506
Hello.

225
00:16:56,615 --> 00:16:58,674
I thought you deserted us.

226
00:16:58,784 --> 00:17:01,878
- I've had a busy week.
- Busy two weeks.

227
00:17:01,987 --> 00:17:04,547
- Have you been buying more trees?
- How did you guess?

228
00:17:04,656 --> 00:17:08,285
Well, l... I was just going to make
some fresh coffee.

229
00:17:08,394 --> 00:17:11,454
- Would you like some?
- No, thank you. I'm all finished.

230
00:17:11,563 --> 00:17:15,556
That means we're not going
to see you again until next spring.

231
00:17:15,667 --> 00:17:19,501
I won't be coming back
next spring.

232
00:17:19,605 --> 00:17:21,664
I'm giving up
my maintenance work.

233
00:17:21,774 --> 00:17:23,867
Growing trees
is a full-time job.

234
00:17:23,976 --> 00:17:26,137
At least the way
I want to do it.

235
00:17:26,245 --> 00:17:28,543
Don't worry.
I'll find you someone.

236
00:17:29,648 --> 00:17:31,616
Thank you.

237
00:17:31,717 --> 00:17:36,416
Well, I guess this is good-bye.
I wish you luck with your trees.

238
00:17:36,522 --> 00:17:40,652
- Remember the silver tip spruce?
- Yes?

239
00:17:40,759 --> 00:17:43,523
I was wondering,
if you're not too busy,

240
00:17:43,629 --> 00:17:46,530
you might like to come over
to my place and see them.

241
00:17:47,966 --> 00:17:51,094
Well, I'm sorry,
but I'm afraid I can't today.

242
00:17:51,203 --> 00:17:54,570
Oh, well, of course,
if you can't.

243
00:18:00,345 --> 00:18:03,405
- Oh, Mr. Kirby.
- Yes, Mrs. Scott?

244
00:18:05,884 --> 00:18:08,717
Well, I was just thinking
that maybe if...

245
00:18:09,955 --> 00:18:12,515
You've changed your mind?

246
00:18:16,929 --> 00:18:18,988
All right! Let's go!

247
00:18:36,915 --> 00:18:38,906
It certainly is
out in the woods.

248
00:18:39,017 --> 00:18:41,884
- Not what you expected?
- I thought you lived here.

249
00:18:41,987 --> 00:18:43,887
I do.

250
00:18:53,765 --> 00:18:57,963
I can see that a woman might not
like it, but it does very well for me.

251
00:18:58,070 --> 00:19:00,538
If one likes to live
in a glass house.

252
00:19:00,639 --> 00:19:03,574
At night when I'm in bed
I can see the stars in the sky.

253
00:19:03,675 --> 00:19:06,769
- And you have your plants.
- Mm-hmm.

254
00:19:10,349 --> 00:19:14,342
- What a lovely color.
- That's a coleus.

255
00:19:14,453 --> 00:19:17,013
The one on the other side
is a dracaena.

256
00:19:17,122 --> 00:19:19,215
Grows into sort of a tree.

257
00:19:19,324 --> 00:19:22,885
- Oh, where are the trees?
- Right outside.

258
00:19:23,996 --> 00:19:26,362
After you.

259
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:30,662
Of course, they're only
five year olds, but...

260
00:19:30,769 --> 00:19:34,569
Five years to grow that?
Don't you ever get impatient?

261
00:19:34,673 --> 00:19:37,608
If you're impatient,
you have no business growing trees.

262
00:19:37,709 --> 00:19:41,941
Someday I'm gonna tear down the old mill
and put in more silver tip spruce there.

263
00:19:42,047 --> 00:19:45,039
- What's in the old mill?
- Oh, nothing.

264
00:19:45,150 --> 00:19:47,846
Could we go in?
I love to poke around old buildings.

265
00:19:58,597 --> 00:20:01,088
[Door Creaking]

266
00:20:11,210 --> 00:20:16,238
That's the old millstone.
Grandpa used to grind his flour here.

267
00:20:16,348 --> 00:20:18,543
Watch the cobwebs.

268
00:20:27,626 --> 00:20:31,892
That's the loft where
he used to store his grain.

269
00:20:31,997 --> 00:20:34,056
Oh!

270
00:20:36,068 --> 00:20:38,536
Oh, look.

271
00:20:40,839 --> 00:20:45,742
Oh! Wedgwood.
If we could only find the pieces.

272
00:20:45,844 --> 00:20:49,837
- What would you do with it?
- I'd steal it. I love wedgwood.

273
00:20:49,948 --> 00:20:54,180
It was probably thrown there
because the pieces were missing.

274
00:20:54,286 --> 00:20:57,380
Better leave it.

275
00:21:00,325 --> 00:21:02,816
Seen enough?

276
00:21:02,928 --> 00:21:06,329
No, I haven't even started.

277
00:21:06,431 --> 00:21:09,423
I suppose these old beams
are rotted.

278
00:21:09,534 --> 00:21:13,402
No, they're oak.
They're good for another hundred years.

279
00:21:18,477 --> 00:21:21,173
And the stairs?
What's up there?

280
00:21:21,280 --> 00:21:24,477
I don't know.
I haven't been there since I was a kid.

281
00:21:24,583 --> 00:21:28,144
- It's pretty dirty... full of cobwebs.
- Oh, I don't mind.

282
00:21:31,723 --> 00:21:35,215
Did the bird
frighten you, Mrs. Scott?

283
00:21:35,327 --> 00:21:39,286
Well, it...
it would frighten anyone.

284
00:21:43,302 --> 00:21:47,466
A fireplace.
Why, that makes it perfect.

285
00:21:47,572 --> 00:21:49,472
Perfect? For what?

286
00:21:49,574 --> 00:21:52,338
Why, a perfect place
for you to live.

287
00:21:52,444 --> 00:21:55,345
It would take a lot of work,
but it'd be worth it.

288
00:21:55,447 --> 00:21:58,473
- I've got a place to live.
- Oh.

289
00:21:58,583 --> 00:22:01,051
You don't intend to live
in that room all your life.

290
00:22:01,153 --> 00:22:04,145
- I hadn't thought about it.
- You'll have to one of these days.

291
00:22:04,256 --> 00:22:07,748
- You'll meet a nice girl...
- I've met plenty of girls.

292
00:22:07,859 --> 00:22:11,158
Nice and otherwise.

293
00:22:12,631 --> 00:22:15,395
Well, not the right one.

294
00:22:15,500 --> 00:22:19,095
And when you do...
Or do you think you're not susceptible?

295
00:22:19,204 --> 00:22:22,196
No. I don't think that.

296
00:22:24,343 --> 00:22:27,972
Well, it's getting
a little late.

297
00:22:28,080 --> 00:22:32,210
I'm sorry. I wasn't
trying to arrange your life.

298
00:22:33,719 --> 00:22:37,348
After all, it's
none of my business.

299
00:23:09,988 --> 00:23:12,456
[Dove Cooing]

300
00:23:12,557 --> 00:23:14,991
[Door Creaking, Closing]

301
00:23:31,009 --> 00:23:35,002
I'm going upstate to buy some trees
for some friends of mine.

302
00:23:35,113 --> 00:23:38,640
I'll be gone a couple of weeks.
I'll see you when I get back.

303
00:23:38,750 --> 00:23:41,310
- No, l...
- I'll see you.

304
00:24:17,689 --> 00:24:19,714
- Hello, Cary!
- Hello, Sara.

305
00:24:19,825 --> 00:24:23,989
I dropped by to invite you for dinner
tonight. Mona and Mark are coming.

306
00:24:24,095 --> 00:24:26,996
- Mona?
- I know, but I owe them a dinner.

307
00:24:27,098 --> 00:24:30,864
Besides, Mona can be amusing
unless you happen to be her target.

308
00:24:30,969 --> 00:24:35,599
I suppose I should say yes. I haven't
been out since harvey left town.

309
00:24:35,707 --> 00:24:39,336
But mona...
I didn't mean that the way it sounded.

310
00:24:39,444 --> 00:24:42,174
You can't sit around here
with nothing to do.

311
00:24:42,280 --> 00:24:44,441
You should at least
get a television set.

312
00:24:44,549 --> 00:24:46,517
- Oh, no!
- Why?

313
00:24:46,618 --> 00:24:49,018
Because it's supposed
to be the last refuge for lonely women?

314
00:24:49,120 --> 00:24:52,248
That's very sweet of you,
but I don't want a television.

315
00:24:52,357 --> 00:24:55,326
All right, but I've already spoken
to the local television man about you.

316
00:24:55,427 --> 00:24:57,691
- That charming Mr. Weeks.
- [Doorbell Ringing]

317
00:24:57,796 --> 00:25:00,993
- You really should get one...
- Excuse me.

318
00:25:07,172 --> 00:25:10,039
- Hello.
- Hello.

319
00:25:10,141 --> 00:25:13,474
I was just going to drop in
on some friends of mine.

320
00:25:13,578 --> 00:25:15,705
I thought you might like
to come along.

321
00:25:18,884 --> 00:25:21,785
Well... won't you come in?

322
00:25:21,887 --> 00:25:23,787
Thank you.

323
00:25:24,990 --> 00:25:28,289
They'll probably ask us
to stay for dinner.

324
00:25:30,428 --> 00:25:33,056
I have a guest right this minute.
Could you wait?

325
00:25:33,164 --> 00:25:36,031
- Cary?
- Yes, Sara?

326
00:25:36,134 --> 00:25:38,659
- Mrs. Warren, this is Mr...
- Kirby.

327
00:25:38,770 --> 00:25:41,534
How do you do? I can't stay.
I'll see you tonight.

328
00:25:41,640 --> 00:25:47,044
Would you be terribly disappointed
if I didn't come tonight?

329
00:25:47,145 --> 00:25:51,138
Of course not! I understand if you're
not in the mood for Mona's gossip.

330
00:25:51,249 --> 00:25:54,582
- We'll make it next week. Bye.
- Good-bye, Mrs. Warren.

331
00:26:00,225 --> 00:26:03,456
You are coming.

332
00:26:04,563 --> 00:26:08,363
Well... Yes.

333
00:26:08,466 --> 00:26:12,527
It'll be cold by the time we get back.
Better take a warm coat.

334
00:26:28,954 --> 00:26:31,514
Hey, Mick!

335
00:26:33,191 --> 00:26:35,921
I'll be right back.
Hey, Mick!

336
00:26:38,129 --> 00:26:40,529
- Hi, Ron.
- Hi.

337
00:26:51,209 --> 00:26:53,473
- Hi!
- [Ron] Hi!

338
00:26:53,578 --> 00:26:56,513
- I'd like you to meet Mick and Alida.
- How do you do?

339
00:26:56,615 --> 00:26:58,515
- Hello.
- Hello, Cary.

340
00:26:58,617 --> 00:27:00,517
What a nice surprise.
Come on upstairs.

341
00:27:00,619 --> 00:27:02,610
- You're just in time for the clambake.
- Good!

342
00:27:02,721 --> 00:27:05,212
- Come on in.
- Thank you.

343
00:27:05,323 --> 00:27:07,723
- It's a little chilly in here.
- I'll have a fire in a moment.

344
00:27:07,826 --> 00:27:09,726
I'll take your coat.

345
00:27:09,828 --> 00:27:12,058
- Say, Ron, why don't you start it?
- Okay.

346
00:27:12,163 --> 00:27:15,223
I'll make an anderson special, a talent
I developed on the ulcer circuit.

347
00:27:15,333 --> 00:27:17,563
Freely translated,
the advertising business.

348
00:27:17,669 --> 00:27:21,298
You wouldn't believe it,
but he was once a v.i.p. In New York.

349
00:27:21,406 --> 00:27:25,900
No, you're the one that taught him
to be a very independent person.

350
00:27:26,011 --> 00:27:28,502
The only thing he ever taught me was
how to open a wine bottle with my teeth.

351
00:27:28,613 --> 00:27:31,241
To hear them tell it,
you'd think they spent the war...

352
00:27:31,349 --> 00:27:33,510
crawling from
wine cellar to wine cellar.

353
00:27:33,618 --> 00:27:37,384
- [Ron] We did!
- Make cary comfortable, will you, Ron?

354
00:27:37,489 --> 00:27:40,947
All right.
Sit down, Cary.

355
00:27:41,059 --> 00:27:43,960
- What did you say about me outside?
- When?

356
00:27:44,062 --> 00:27:47,395
When he looked at me
and laughed.

357
00:27:47,499 --> 00:27:50,662
I told him you had the prettiest legs
I'd ever seen.

358
00:27:50,769 --> 00:27:53,738
- Here is the Anderson special.
- Oh, it's heavy!

359
00:27:53,838 --> 00:27:55,965
Put the cauldron on the fire,
will you, old man?

360
00:27:56,074 --> 00:27:58,304
- You're in for a shore dinner.
- Hope you like it.

361
00:27:58,410 --> 00:28:00,344
- I do.
- Good!

362
00:28:00,445 --> 00:28:03,505
- Here you are, Cary. Alida.
- Thank you.

363
00:28:03,615 --> 00:28:08,518
Here's to those who wish us well, and
those that don't can go to hackensack.

364
00:28:08,620 --> 00:28:11,145
Salud.

365
00:28:11,256 --> 00:28:13,554
- How do you like it?
- Marvelous. What's in them?

366
00:28:13,658 --> 00:28:17,924
First you get some ice, two jiggers
of clements, a little twist of...

367
00:28:18,029 --> 00:28:20,327
Mick, stop it!

368
00:28:20,432 --> 00:28:24,801
- You can help me bring up some wine.
- We'll be right back.

369
00:28:24,903 --> 00:28:28,395
- How many are coming tonight?
- You never can tell.

370
00:28:28,506 --> 00:28:31,998
That's so true.
You never know with that boy.

371
00:28:32,110 --> 00:28:34,010
Which means I better get busy.

372
00:28:34,112 --> 00:28:37,673
- Can I help you?
- Oh, no, make yourself comfortable.

373
00:28:50,895 --> 00:28:55,662
''The mass of men lead lives
of quiet desperation.

374
00:28:55,767 --> 00:28:59,203
''Why should we be in such
desperate haste to succeed?

375
00:29:04,209 --> 00:29:07,645
''Lf a man does not keep pace
with his companions,

376
00:29:07,746 --> 00:29:10,544
''perhaps it is because
he hears a different drummer.

377
00:29:10,648 --> 00:29:14,482
'' Let him step to the music
which he hears, however measured...

378
00:29:14,586 --> 00:29:17,214
or far away.''

379
00:29:17,322 --> 00:29:20,086
- Why, that's beautiful.
- That's mick's bible.

380
00:29:20,191 --> 00:29:22,659
He quotes from it
constantly.

381
00:29:22,761 --> 00:29:26,288
- Please let me help.
- All right. Come on.

382
00:29:26,397 --> 00:29:29,025
Kind of heavy.

383
00:29:29,134 --> 00:29:32,126
- Is it Ron's bible too?
- Hmm?

384
00:29:32,237 --> 00:29:34,797
I don't think Ron's ever read it.
He just lives it.

385
00:29:34,906 --> 00:29:39,400
- Put it in the middle.
- All right.

386
00:29:39,511 --> 00:29:41,445
Thank you.

387
00:29:41,546 --> 00:29:43,878
- Alida?
- Hmm?

388
00:29:43,982 --> 00:29:48,851
What did you mean when
you said that ron taught Mick?

389
00:29:48,953 --> 00:29:53,822
Well, it's kind of
hard to explain.

390
00:29:53,925 --> 00:29:58,294
I guess all of us
are looking for security these days.

391
00:29:58,396 --> 00:30:02,765
You see, Mick thought...
Well, like a lot of other people...

392
00:30:02,867 --> 00:30:06,860
that if he had money and an important
position it would make him secure.

393
00:30:06,971 --> 00:30:10,771
Then when he met Ron who didn't have
either one and didn't seem to need them,

394
00:30:10,875 --> 00:30:13,002
He was completely baffled.

395
00:30:13,111 --> 00:30:17,810
The answer was so simple it took
Mick a long time to figure it out.

396
00:30:17,916 --> 00:30:20,009
What was the answer?

397
00:30:21,119 --> 00:30:24,316
To thine own self be true.
That's Ron.

398
00:30:24,422 --> 00:30:28,290
You see, Ron's security
comes from inside himself.

399
00:30:28,393 --> 00:30:30,293
Nothing can ever
take it away.

400
00:30:30,395 --> 00:30:35,059
Ron absolutely refuses to let
unimportant things become important.

401
00:30:35,166 --> 00:30:39,432
That's what Mick
and I were doing. We were.

402
00:30:39,537 --> 00:30:43,439
In fact, things got so bad
between us that...

403
00:30:43,541 --> 00:30:46,704
right before he went to Korea
we were thinking of a separation.

404
00:30:46,811 --> 00:30:50,679
Oh, no.
You seem so happy.

405
00:30:50,782 --> 00:30:55,685
Not then.
We weren't happy then.

406
00:30:55,787 --> 00:31:00,053
Our whole life was devoted
to keeping up with theJoneses.

407
00:31:00,158 --> 00:31:03,855
But when Mick was wounded
and had a lot of time to think,

408
00:31:03,962 --> 00:31:07,056
He decided to get off
that merry-go-round.

409
00:31:07,165 --> 00:31:10,100
When he came back,
he put it right up to me.

410
00:31:10,201 --> 00:31:12,032
- [Woman] Alida!
- Yeah?

411
00:31:12,136 --> 00:31:14,832
My room's a mess,
but don't bother. I'm off!

412
00:31:14,939 --> 00:31:18,306
- Wait!
- I can't, I'm late. See you tomorrow.

413
00:31:18,409 --> 00:31:23,039
- Mary Ann! What time?
- I don't know. In the afternoon.

414
00:31:23,147 --> 00:31:25,741
- [Mary Ann] Ron!
- [Ron Chuckling] Mary Ann!

415
00:31:25,850 --> 00:31:28,148
- I didn't know you were coming.
- Why, sure.

416
00:31:28,253 --> 00:31:30,153
- [Mary Ann] Now I'm disappointed.
- Why?

417
00:31:30,255 --> 00:31:33,918
I thought it was just another
of Mick and Alida's get-togethers.

418
00:31:34,025 --> 00:31:38,052
- If i'd known... I want a rain check.
- Name it.

419
00:31:38,162 --> 00:31:40,892
- To go swimming with you again.
- It's too cold.

420
00:31:40,999 --> 00:31:43,593
- How about sailing then?
- Fine.

421
00:31:43,701 --> 00:31:46,898
- Before it gets too cold for that too.
- I have a windbreaker.

422
00:31:47,005 --> 00:31:49,667
- What about me?
- You'll be warm enough.

423
00:31:49,774 --> 00:31:52,174
You never take me seriously.

424
00:31:52,277 --> 00:31:54,177
[Alida]
Drive carefully, Mary Ann!

425
00:31:54,279 --> 00:31:56,941
My young cousin.
She's spending the winter with us.

426
00:31:57,048 --> 00:32:01,883
She thought our party sounded dull, so
she arranged to stay with a girlfriend.

427
00:32:01,986 --> 00:32:04,887
- Think this will be enough?
- Yes.

428
00:32:04,989 --> 00:32:07,048
Mick, would you give me a hand,
darling?

429
00:32:07,158 --> 00:32:09,456
What have you been doing? I thought
you'd have the heavy work done.

430
00:32:09,560 --> 00:32:12,120
- Put the bottles down.
- Think 16 will be enough?

431
00:32:12,230 --> 00:32:16,963
- With this crowd? Thanks.
- You betcha.

432
00:32:17,068 --> 00:32:21,835
Oh, no, thanks, honey, but there's some
tablecloths in the right-hand drawer.

433
00:32:21,940 --> 00:32:25,000
- Lobsters have arrived!
- Look, I got 'em!

434
00:32:25,109 --> 00:32:27,043
Hey, Manuel! Thank you!

435
00:32:27,145 --> 00:32:29,136
I caught myself
this morning!

436
00:32:29,247 --> 00:32:32,080
- This is Manuel, the lobster king.
- Hello!

437
00:32:32,183 --> 00:32:34,981
My pleasure.
She's beautiful! My wife Rozanne.

438
00:32:35,086 --> 00:32:37,350
! Que bonita!
! Tanto gusto!

439
00:32:37,455 --> 00:32:39,480
- Mi hija, Marguerita.
- How do you do?

440
00:32:39,590 --> 00:32:42,286
Marguerita is a very good cook.
She makes this corn bread...

441
00:32:42,393 --> 00:32:45,954
Hey, hey, hey!
Get your paws off!

442
00:32:46,064 --> 00:32:50,057
- [Rozanne] Alida!
- It's so good seeing you.

443
00:32:50,168 --> 00:32:53,626
You will love the lobsters.
Mick, let me help you.

444
00:32:53,738 --> 00:32:55,933
Well, Grandpa! How are ya?
Let me take your coat.

445
00:32:56,040 --> 00:32:59,635
Cary, this is Grandpa Adams.
He's a beekeeper and artist.

446
00:32:59,744 --> 00:33:02,212
- You must see his one-man show.
- Why, I hope to.

447
00:33:02,313 --> 00:33:06,306
Of course, Miss Cary, I'm not
an abstractionist. Strictly primitive.

448
00:33:06,417 --> 00:33:08,749
- You know everybody here.
- [Alida] Come on in, Grandpa!

449
00:33:08,853 --> 00:33:11,014
Edna, what a beautiful cake!

450
00:33:11,122 --> 00:33:15,616
Meet Miss Pidway, head of the Audubon
Society and an outstanding bird-watcher.

451
00:33:15,727 --> 00:33:17,820
- How do you do?
- How do you do?

452
00:33:17,929 --> 00:33:21,023
- Glass of wine, Manuel?
- Two glasses of wine for Manuel!

453
00:33:21,132 --> 00:33:25,501
- A dollar says you can't.
- Why, put it on your bill.

454
00:33:25,603 --> 00:33:28,003
I've never seen this
done before.

455
00:33:29,307 --> 00:33:32,367
- I wouldn't try that with my new teeth!
- Oh, no.

456
00:33:44,422 --> 00:33:47,448
? My, my, my
I have rovey eye ?

457
00:33:47,558 --> 00:33:50,254
? How he fly
all around the town ?

458
00:33:50,361 --> 00:33:52,886
? Eye, eye, eye
every passerby ?

459
00:33:52,997 --> 00:33:56,524
? He look-a her up
he look-a her down
ooh-hoo ?

460
00:33:56,634 --> 00:33:58,966
?? Ooh-hoo ??

461
00:33:59,070 --> 00:34:01,538
- ??Lady, what a pleasant view ??
- Thank you.

462
00:34:04,542 --> 00:34:07,443
? I make the flirty eye
at you ?

463
00:34:07,545 --> 00:34:11,003
??My, my, my, no more rovey eye
No more fly ??

464
00:34:11,115 --> 00:34:13,208
